{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HbYiYRDpKC8zyDVXcCf7wL","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"question\",\n3\t  \"questions\": [\n4\t    {\n5\t      \"id\": \"q1\",\n6\t      \"question\": \"Should src/config.py use python-dotenv for .env file loading, or a stdlib-only approach (manually parsing the file)? The project has no requirements.txt or pyproject.toml, and no existing dotenv dependency.\",\n7\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n8\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Using python-dotenv is the standard approach but introduces an external dependency with no existing dependency management in place. A stdlib-only parser avoids that but is less robust.\"\n9\t    },\n10\t    {\n11\t      \"id\": \"q2\",\n12\t      \"question\": \"The task says 'src/config.py' but the main backend already lives in backend/ and has its own backend/inference/config.py. Is src/ the correct location, or should this go in backend/?\",\n13\t      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n14\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Placing a config loader in src/ when all existing Python backend code lives in backend/ could create a disjointed layout. However, src/ already has greeting.py from a prior task, suggesting it may be a separate module area.\"\n15\t    },\n16\t    {\n17\t      \"id\": \"q3\",\n18\t      \"question\": \"The existing backend/server.py reads env vars directly via os.environ.get(). Should load_config() integrate with or remain independent of that pattern?\",\n19\t      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n20\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"If this config module is meant to eventually replace the scattered os.environ.get() calls in server.py, the interface matters. If it's standalone, the design is simpler.\"\n21\t    },\n22\t    {\n23\t      \"id\": \"q4\",\n24\t      \"question\": \"Should DEBUG be parsed as a boolean from string env var values (e.g., 'true', '1', 'yes') and if so, which values should be truthy? The backend already has a _read_bool_env helper.\",\n25\t      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n26\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Environment variables are always strings. The conversion semantics for DEBUG affect correctness — accepting only 'True' vs also '1'/'yes' changes user experience.\"\n27\t    }\n28\t  ],\n29\t  \"assumptions\": [\n30\t    {\n31\t      \"id\": \"a1\",\n32\t      \"assumption\": \"The module should be placed at src/config.py as stated in the task description, even though main backend code lives in backend/.\",\n33\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n34\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Would need to create backend/config.py instead and adjust imports.\"\n35\t    },\n36\t    {\n37\t      \"id\": \"a2\",\n38\t      \"assumption\": \"python-dotenv can be used as a dependency for .env file loading, since it's the de facto standard for this pattern in Python.\",\n39\t      \"confidence\": 0.7,\n40\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Would need to implement a manual .env parser using only stdlib, handling comments, quotes, and export prefixes.\"\n41\t    },\n42\t    {\n43\t      \"id\": \"a3\",\n44\t      \"assumption\": \"load_config() should return a plain dict like {'APP_NAME': 'MyApp', 'DEBUG': False} with env vars taking precedence over .env file values, and .env values taking precedence over defaults.\",\n45\t      \"confidence\": 0.95,\n46\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Might need a different data structure (dataclass, NamedTuple) or different precedence order.\"\n47\t    },\n48\t    {\n49\t      \"id\": \"a4\",\n50\t      \"assumption\": \"DEBUG should accept common truthy string values ('true', '1', 'yes') case-insensitively, consistent with the existing _read_bool_env pattern in backend/server.py.\",\n51\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n52\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Would need to use a stricter or different boolean parsing strategy.\"\n53\t    },\n54\t    {\n55\t      \"id\": \"a5\",\n56\t      \"assumption\": \"A corresponding test file (tests/test_config.py) should be created alongside the module.\",\n57\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n58\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Tests might not be needed or might go in a different location.\"\n59\t    }\n60\t  ],\n61\t  \"spawn_children\": false,\n62\t  \"children\": []\n63\t}\n64\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bfd48eab-4e23-40fb-bc34-d5942803fb70","uuid":"706a2354-71a9-43a6-9cc4-df3c51336bb9","timestamp":"2026-04-11T06:12:35.530Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/temporal-worktrees/task-artifact-test-001/.fleet/tasks/artifact-test-001/questions.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"question\",\n  \"questions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q1\",\n      \"question\": \"Should src/config.py use python-dotenv for .env file loading, or a stdlib-only approach (manually parsing the file)? The project has no requirements.txt or pyproject.toml, and no existing dotenv dependency.\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"Using python-dotenv is the standard approach but introduces an external dependency with no existing dependency management in place. A stdlib-only parser avoids that but is less robust.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q2\",\n      \"question\": \"The task says 'src/config.py' but the main backend already lives in backend/ and has its own backend/inference/config.py. Is src/ the correct location, or should this go in backend/?\",\n      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"Placing a config loader in src/ when all existing Python backend code lives in backend/ could create a disjointed layout. However, src/ already has greeting.py from a prior task, suggesting it may be a separate module area.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q3\",\n      \"question\": \"The existing backend/server.py reads env vars directly via os.environ.get(). Should load_config() integrate with or remain independent of that pattern?\",\n      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"If this config module is meant to eventually replace the scattered os.environ.get() calls in serve